The inhabitants of New Netherland, the [New Netherlanders](/New_Netherlander), were not exclusively Dutch, and the colony never developed into a homogeneous society. [2] Governor [Peter Minuit](/Peter_Minuit), for instance, was a [Walloon](/Walloons) born in what is now Germany, who also spoke English and worked for a Dutch company. [53] The term [New Netherland Dutch](/New_Netherland_Dutch) generally encompasses all Europeans who settled there, [1] but the population also included Africans, [Indo-Caribbeans](/Indo-Caribbean), South Americans, and even indigenous peoples who played an integral role in the society. While Dutch was the official language and likely the *lingua franca* of the province, a variety of other languages were also spoken. [2]

[Algonquian languages](/Algonquian_languages) were spoken by the indigenous inhabitants. Walloons and [Huguenots](/Huguenots) typically spoke French, while Scandinavians and Germans brought their own tongues. It is probable that the Africans in Manhattan spoke their native languages but were taught Dutch from 1638 onwards by Adam Roelantsz van Dokkum. [54] The arrival of refugees from [New Holland](/Dutch_Brazil) in Brazil may have introduced speakers of Portuguese, Spanish, and [Ladino](/Ladino_language), with Hebrew used as a liturgical language. Commercial activities in the harbor were likely conducted simultaneously in any of these languages. [55]

Slavery was introduced by the Dutch West India Company in 1625 with the importation of 11 enslaved black individuals who worked as farmers, fur traders, and builders. These enslaved people possessed a few basic rights, and families were generally kept intact. They were permitted to attend the Dutch Reformed Church and could be married by its ministers, with their children eligible for baptism. Enslaved individuals could testify in court, sign legal documents, and initiate civil actions against white colonists. Some were allowed to work in their off-hours, earning wages comparable to those paid to white workers. When the colony fell to the English, the company freed the enslaved population, thereby establishing an early nucleus of free Black people. [56]

The [Union of Utrecht](/Union_of_Utrecht), the foundational document of the Dutch Republic signed in 1579, proclaimed that "everyone shall remain free in religion and that no one may be persecuted or investigated because of religion." However, the [Dutch West India Company](/Dutch_West_India_Company) designated the Reformed Church as the official religious institution of New Netherland. [3] Its successor church is the Reformed Church in America. The colonists were instructed to attract indigenous peoples and other non-believers to God's word "through attitude and by example," but not to "persecute someone by reason of his religion, and to leave everyone the freedom of his conscience." The laws and ordinances of the states of Holland were incorporated by reference into the initial instructions provided to the settlers on Governors Island in 1624. During Stuyvesant's governorship, two pivotal cases upheld this principle: the official granting of full residency rights to both [Ashkenazi](/Ashkenazi_Jews) and [Sephardi Jews](/Sephardi_Jews) in New Amsterdam in 1655, and the [Flushing Remonstrance](/Flushing_Remonstrance) involving [Quakers](/Quakers) in 1657.

The territory claimed by New Netherland extended from areas in [Canada](/Canada) down to [Delaware](/Delaware). [57] [58]

***

### Expansion and Incursion

#### South River and New Sweden

Aside from the second [Fort Nassau](/Fort_Nassau_(South)) and the small community that supported it, settlement along the [Zuyd Rivier](/Delaware_River) remained limited. The settlement established by the patroons [Samuel Blommaert](/Samuel_Blommaert) and [Samuel Godijn] at [Zwaanendael](/Zwaanendael_Colony) was destroyed by the local indigenous population shortly after its founding in 1631, during the absence of their agent, [David Pietersen de Vries]. [59]

[Peter Minuit](/Peter_Minuit), who had secured a deed for [Manhattan](/Manhattan) from the Lenape and was subsequently dismissed as director, recognized that the Dutch lacked the capacity to defend the southern flank of their North American territory. Furthermore, they had not established treaties with or purchased land from the [Lenape](/Lenape) in that region. After securing support from the Queen of [Sweden](/Sweden), Minuit chose the west bank of the [Delaware River](/Delaware_River) to establish a colony in 1638, which he named [New Sweden](/New_Sweden). As anticipated, the government in New Amsterdam took no action beyond lodging a formal protest. Small settlements, centered around [Fort Christina](/Fort_Christina), gradually emerged as the colony expanded, primarily populated by [Swedes](/Swedes), [Finns](/Finns), and [Dutch](/Dutch_people). [60]

In 1651, the Dutch dismantled Fort Nassau and constructed [Fort Casimir](/Fort_Casimir) on the west bank, aiming to disrupt trade and reassert their control. Three years later, Fort Casimir was captured by the Swedes, who renamed it Fort Trinity. In 1655, [Stuyvesant](/Peter_Stuyvesant) led a military expedition and successfully regained control of the region, renaming its principal settlement "[New Amstel](/New_Amstel)" (Nieuw-Amstel). [61] While Stuyvesant was engaged in the conquest of New Sweden, several villages and farms in the [Manhattans](/New_York_Harbor) area, specifically [Pavonia](/Pavonia,_New_Netherland) and [Staten Island](/Staten_Island), were attacked in an incident known as the [Peach War](/Peach_War). These raids are sometimes attributed to retaliation for the murder of a Munsee woman who was attempting to pick a peach, although it is also possible they were intended to disrupt the attack on New Sweden. [25] [62] [63]

In 1663, a new, experimental settlement was initiated on [Delaware Bay](/Delaware_Bay), just before the [British](/British_people) takeover in 1664. [Franciscus van den Enden](/Franciscus_van_den_Enden) had drafted a charter for a utopian society that advocated for equal education for all social classes, communal ownership of property, and a democratically elected government. [25] [Pieter Corneliszoon Plockhoy](/Pieter_Corneliszoon_Plockhoy) attempted to establish such a settlement near the site of Zwaanendael, but it was largely destroyed by the British in 1664. [64]

#### Fresh River and New England

A small number of Dutch settlers established homes in New Netherland at [Fort Goede Hoop](/Fort_Goede_Hoop) on the [Fresh River](/Connecticut_River). As early as 1637, English settlers from the [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony) began to colonize the riverbanks and [Lange Eylandt](/Long_Island), some with the explicit permission of the colonial government, while others proceeded with complete disregard for its authority. The English colonies experienced more rapid growth than New Netherland, largely driven by a desire to establish communities with strong religious foundations, rather than purely commercial interests. The *wal*, or rampart, in New Amsterdam (later [Wall Street](/Wall_Street)) was initially constructed out of fear of an impending English invasion. [59]

Initially, contact between New Englanders and New Netherlanders was limited. However, as the English population swelled and territorial disputes intensified, the two provinces engaged in direct diplomatic relations. The [New England Confederation](/New_England_Confederation) was formed in 1643 as a political and military alliance comprising the English colonies of [Massachusetts](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony), [Plymouth](/Plymouth_Colony), [Connecticut](/Connecticut_Colony), and [New Haven](/New_Haven_Colony). [65] Both Connecticut and [New Haven](/New_Haven,_Connecticut) occupied lands claimed by the United Provinces. Nevertheless, the Dutch lacked the population and military strength to effectively defend their territorial claims, leaving them with little recourse but to protest the increasing influx of English settlers. [59]

Through the [Treaty of Hartford](/Treaty_of_Hartford_(1650)) in 1650, Stuyvesant provisionally ceded the Connecticut River region to New England. This treaty established New Netherland's eastern border at a point 50 Dutch miles (approximately [250 km](/Dutch_units_of_measurement)) west of the Connecticut River's mouth on the mainland and just west of [Oyster Bay](/Oyster_Bay_(hamlet),_New_York) on Long Island. The Dutch West India Company refused to ratify the treaty, but failed to reach any alternative agreement with the English. Consequently, the Hartford Treaty effectively served as the de facto border. The territory of Connecticut was largely assimilated into New England. [59]

***

### Capitulation, Restitution, and Concession

In March 1664, [Charles II of England](/Charles_II_of_England), Scotland, and Ireland resolved to annex New Netherland, with the stated aim "to bring all his Kingdoms under one form of government, both in church and state, and to install the Anglican government as in old England." The directors of the Dutch West India Company believed that the religious freedom offered in New Netherland would dissuade English colonists from actively seeking their removal. They wrote to Director-General [Peter Stuyvesant](/Peter_Stuyvesant):

> "[W]e are in hopes that as the English at the north (in New Netherland) have removed mostly from old England for the causes aforesaid, they will not give us henceforth so much trouble, but prefer to live free under us at peace with their consciences than to risk getting rid of our authority and then falling again under a government from which they had formerly fled." [66]

On August 27, 1664, four English frigates, under the command of [Richard Nicolls](/Richard_Nicolls), sailed into [New Amsterdam's harbor](/New_York_Harbor) and demanded the surrender of New Netherland. [67] [68] The [capture of New Amsterdam](/Capture_of_New_Amsterdam) was met with no resistance. Prior requests for military support to protect the Dutch colonists from their English neighbors and [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) had been ignored, leaving New Amsterdam effectively defenseless. Stuyvesant, however, managed to negotiate favorable terms from his "too powerful enemies." [69]

Article VIII of these [terms](/Articles_of_Surrender_of_New_Netherland) guaranteed that [New Netherlanders](/New_Netherlander) "shall keep and enjoy the liberty of their consciences in religion" under English rule. While these Articles were largely upheld in New Amsterdam and the Hudson River Valley, they were violated in another sector of the [conquest of New Netherland](/Conquest_of_New_Netherland) along the Delaware River. There, [Colonel](/Colonel) Sir Robert Carr appropriated property for his personal use and sold Dutch [prisoners of war](/Prisoner_of_war) into slavery. Nicolls eventually compelled Carr to return some of the confiscated property. [70] [71] Furthermore, a [Mennonite](/Mennonite) settlement led by [Pieter Corneliszoon Plockhoy](/Pieter_Corneliszoon_Plockhoy) near [Lewes, Delaware](/Lewes,_Delaware) was destroyed. [72]

The [Treaty of Breda](/Treaty_of_Breda_(1667)), signed in 1667, brought an end to the [Second Anglo-Dutch War](/Second_Anglo-Dutch_War). The Dutch did not press their claims on New Netherland, and the existing status quo was maintained, with the Dutch retaining control of [Suriname](/Surinam_(Dutch_colony)) and the nutmeg island of [Run](/Run_(island)).

Within six years, the two nations found themselves at war once more. In August 1673, the Dutch [recaptured New Netherland](/Reconquest_of_New_Netherland) with a fleet of 21 ships, commanded by Vice Admiral [Cornelis Evertsen the Youngest](/Cornelis_Evertsen_the_Youngest) and Commodore [Jacob Binckes](/Jacob_Binckes). This was the largest naval force seen in America at that time. [73] They appointed [Anthony Colve](/Anthony_Colve) as governor and renamed the city New Orange, a tribute to the enthronement of [William of Orange](/William_III_of_England) as [Stadtholder](/Stadtholder) of Holland in 1672. He would later become King [William III of England](/William_III_of_England) in 1689. [74]

The Dutch Republic found itself in dire financial straits following the conclusion of the [Third Anglo-Dutch War](/Third_Anglo-Dutch_War) in 1672–1674, a period known as the ["disaster years"](/Rampjaar) when the republic faced simultaneous attacks from the French under [Louis XIV](/Louis_XIV), the English, the [Prince-Bishop of Münster](/Prince-Bishop_of_M%C3%BCnster), and the [Archbishop-Elector of Cologne](/Archbishop-Elector_of_Cologne). The [States of Zeeland](/States_of_Zeeland) attempted to persuade the [States of Holland](/States_of_Holland_and_West_Friesland) to assume responsibility for the New Netherland province, but their efforts were unsuccessful. In February 1674, the [Treaty of Westminster](/Treaty_of_Westminster_(1674)) officially ended the war. It was not until November 10, 1674, that the new English governor, [Edmund Andros](/Edmund_Andros), took possession from Governor Anthony Colve. [75]

